# facts

- a CLI for fact-driven development with coding agents
- works with fact sheets — flat lists of validatable atomic facts
- extreme simplicity in everything — code, format, UX

## format

### file
- project root is the directory containing the nearest parent .git
- fact sheets are *.facts files in the project root
- .facts is the default/main fact sheet
- naming is semantic (e.g. cli.facts for CLI-specific facts)
- every line is a heading, a fact, or blank — no other content

### parsing
- headings (# prefixed lines) are extracted first as structure
- each section body is then parsed as YAML
- the format is valid Markdown and valid YAML per-section

### sections
- heading depth maps to hierarchy
- sections are addressable by path (e.g. distribution/npm)
- the CLI treats sections as first-class citizens
- sections are created implicitly when a fact is added to them
- sections are removed when their last fact is deleted

### facts
- each fact is a YAML sequence item (- prefixed)
- a fact can be a plain string or a mapping
- mapping keys: id (optional), label (required), command (optional), tags (optional)
- no other keys are allowed
- plain string facts are equivalent to a mapping with only a label
- each fact is fully atomic and independent

### tags
- tags are freeform @word tokens for filtering and categorisation
- inline syntax: - some fact @mvp @core
- mapping syntax: tags: [mvp, core]
- both can coexist on a single fact — parsed as the union
- tags are stripped from the label before ID hashing and display
- write normalises tags to one location: inline for plain strings, tags key for mappings
- lint flags mixed inline and mapping tags on the same fact
- @implemented is a special tag used by the facts-implement skill
- @implemented is informational — check still runs commands for tagged facts

### identity
- every fact has a short ID derived from a hash of its label (tags stripped)
- IDs are 3 characters by default, extended only on collision
- IDs are computed, not stored in the file
- an explicit id key in a mapping overrides the generated ID
- IDs are stable as long as the label does not change

### validation
- facts with a command are validated programmatically by the CLI
- facts without a command are validated by the agent against the codebase
- commands run via $SHELL, falling back to sh if unset
- working directory is the project root
- exit 0 means the fact holds, non-zero means it fails
- all commands run on every check — no caching
- commands run sequentially
- no timeout by default, configurable per-command via --timeout flag
- fact authors should write fast, idempotent check commands
- manual facts do not affect the exit code
- label: project is a Cargo project
  command: test -f Cargo.toml

## cli

- the CLI is named facts
- written in Rust
- distributed as a single compact binary

### subcommands
- bare facts (no subcommand) defaults to list
- init — scaffold a .facts file, detects well-known framework/runtime combos
- check — run all command-facts, report pass/fail/manual
- list — show facts in file order, purely structural
- add — append a fact to a file and section
- remove — remove a fact by ID, outputs what was removed
- edit — modify a fact by ID, preserves explicit id
- lint — validate that fact sheets are parseable

### init
- creates a .facts file in the project root
- detects well-known framework/runtime combos (e.g. Cargo.toml, package.json)
- scaffolds initial facts based on detected stack

### check
- lints all files first — aborts early on lint errors
- groups output by status: passed, failed, manual
- each fact line shows ID and full path (file > section > label)
- file prefix omitted for .facts (default), shown for other files
- passed facts show the command inline
- failed facts show command, exit code, and stderr
- manual facts are listed without detail
- summary line: N passed, N failed, N manual
- legend at the bottom explains manual marker
- exit 0 if all command-facts pass, non-zero if any fail
- --tags flag accepts a boolean filter expression: "mvp and not blocked"
- --timeout flag sets a per-command timeout
- filter expressions support and, or, not, and parentheses

### list
- same format as check but without status markers
- shows facts in file order
- each fact line shows ID and full path (file > section > label)
- file prefix omitted for .facts (default), shown for other files
- supports filtering: --file, --section, --has-command, --manual
- --tags flag accepts a boolean filter expression
- default target is all *.facts files

### add
- defaults to .facts at the top level
- --section flag targets a specific section (created if needed)
- --file flag targets a specific *.facts file (created if needed)
- --command flag adds a validation command
- --id flag sets an explicit ID
- --tags flag adds tags
- appends to the end of the target section
- file order is canonical

### remove
- takes an ID as argument
- outputs the removed fact
- silent — no confirmation prompt

### edit
- takes an ID as argument
- --label, --command, --id, --tags flags modify respective fields
- --add-tag appends tags without removing existing ones
- --remove-tag removes specific tags
- --tags conflicts with --add-tag and --remove-tag
- preserves explicit id when changing other fields
- when a plain string fact gains a command or id, it becomes a mapping
- tags migrate from inline to tags key when fact becomes a mapping

### lint
- validates that fact sheets are parseable
- reports clear error messages for structural issues
- flags mixed inline and mapping tags on the same fact
- does not run any validation commands

### errors
- every error state has a clear, descriptive error message
- invalid operations exit non-zero

### output
- polished terminal output with color and alignment
- green for pass, red for fail, yellow for manual
- colors disabled when output is not a TTY
- write back is byte-for-byte deterministic
- parse then write with no changes produces identical output

## architecture

- minimal dependencies
- clap for CLI argument parsing
- anyhow for error handling
- integration tests for all user-facing features

## platforms

- linux amd64 and arm64
- macOS amd64 and arm64
- windows amd64

## distribution

### npm
- published as an npm package wrapping the prebuilt binary

### pypi
- published as a PyPI package wrapping the prebuilt binary

### install.sh
- downloads the binary from GitHub releases

## skills

- all skills are agent-agnostic
- all installable via skills.sh
- skill names use facts- prefix to avoid collision
- source is in ./skills/

### facts
- teaches agents how to install and use facts
- source is in ./skills/facts/

### facts-discover
- instructs agent to scan the codebase and make the fact sheet an accurate mirror of reality
- uses subagents to scan different areas of the codebase in parallel
- adds, edits, and removes facts to match what is actually true now
- only records what is — not what should be
- reports what changed at the end
- source is in ./skills/facts-discover/

### facts-implement
- instructs agent to read the fact sheet as a spec and implement all unimplemented facts
- agent decides order and priority based on its understanding of the codebase
- uses subagents to parallelize independent work
- validation commands are the tests — no separate test step
- marks completed facts with @implemented tag using --add-tag
- reports remaining work and blockers if it cannot complete everything
- source is in ./skills/facts-implement/
